title: For Sale:  NITRO Snowboard / Burton Bindings
postcontent:
Offering up a 2010 NITRO "Volume" Snowboard fitted with 2009 Burton "Freestyle" Bindings. The NITRO is 62.5in/158cm tall and is 10.5in/26cm wide. Perfect for riders who have wide feet and are over 180lbs (ideally). It is a standard camber type, all mountain board with still enough flex for popping. Not a park board, but it has a lot of stability which makes it great for practicing at faster speeds and carving. I am 5'7" and currently 217lbs and it rode very well for me. I now consider myself an advanced rider and this carried me very well through my beginner and intermediate phases.

The Burton bindings are Size Large and will fit size 10 and up boots. I wore size 13 boots in them and I still had room for adjustments. These are good all around with a decent response and good cushion.

This gear is generously used but still in good working order. The only serious fault with the board is some slight chipping at the tail (stay away from rocks!) However, the edges are still good and all I really recommend is a good hot waxing. I consider this perfect for someone who is just starting out or trying to downsize from a slightly larger board, someone who regularly rents gear and is looking for a cheaper alternative or maybe someone looking for a back up set.

The board itself was $300 and the bindings were little over $100 brand new.

Asking Price = $180

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mosin Nagant 91/59 carbine
postcontent:
Up for sale/trade is a 91/59 Mosin Nagant carbine. These were 91/30's that were cut down to a 20" barrel sometime during the cold war. They are lighter than the M44 Mosins and quick handling while still keeping the same high power 54r round. The bluing and stock on this particular rifle are excellent, the trigger is also very light and crisp unlike your typical 91/30. The serial numbers are all matching and it passes headspace. It is a beautiful example. 

My only reason for selling/trading is to expand my Finnish Mosin collection,I am looking to trade for a Finnish M39 , but I am interested in any Finn variant. I am willing to add cash or ammo to even out a trade. Let me know if you are interested, thanks!

title: For Sale:  Commemorative Colt Golden Spike Pistol
postcontent: Colt Frontier Scout "Golden Spike 1869-1969", .22 cal. single action revolver.  Unfired in presentation case. Celebrating the 100th anniversity of the joining of the Union Pacific Railroad and the Central Pacific Railroad on May 10, 1860 at Promontory Point, Utah with a golden spike. They said it couldn't be done, but despite hellish weather, Indian attacks and labor problems it happened and this nice Colt "K" Frontier Scout was created in 1969 to commemorate the event. Beautiful little gun with black "Magic" Colt finish on the barrel and frame then gold plating on the cylinder, ejector rod, cylinder pin, hammer, trigger, ejector top and Colt gold monogrammed textured walnut grips. 6" barrel with fixed sights. The slightest cylinder ring, so either has been cocked or this was done at the factory. Very unique! Nicely housed in a plastic presentation box with "1869 Golden Spike 1969" and portraits of the two railroad owners and the two train engines on the top lid. Drawing of the May 10, 1869 event in the inner lid. Revolver rests in a green crushed velvet interior along with a golden spike with the dates on it

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson, Stailess, 8 shot Revolver, Model 627 Pro Series
postcontent:
The Smith and Wesson Model 627 Pro Series is a large-frame revolver chambered in .357 Mag. and .38 Special +P. The Pro Series is one of four in the Model 627 series and the fact that all four shoot the same cartridges is what holds the series together. Otherwise they are all very different. The Pro Series is stainless steel with a matte finish and has a black synthetic grip. It has an adjustable rear sight and an interchangeable front sight, something the other models don’t have. Also, it has a recessed precision crown, which means the muzzle has been cut flat to allow propellant gases to escape evenly in turn improving accuracy. It has a large exposed hammer and a short four-inch barrel. And, it is the least expensive model with a suggested retail price of $969.

S&W recommends the Pro Series for leisure or competitive shooting, and home protection.

postcontent:
This is NOT a Remington Express gun - this is Police Magnum, which is much more durable!

Remington Police Magnums come with a parkerized finish on an 18" barrel (as opposed to a Blued finish on an Express); feature a stronger sear spring and magazine spring; better extractor and ejector, and much more.

Shotgun has rifle sights and has been gone over completely by in-house Remington LE Certified Armorer. This shotgun goes for $650 new in the box if your are Law Enforcement.

Call or text REDACTED



Differences between an Express 870 and a Police Magnum 870:

The 870 Express has been an important part of Remington’s offering to the sporting market. It was designed to meet a price point in the commercial market while still providing classic 870 functionality. All of Remington’s 870’s have interchangeable parts, even if they have cosmetic differences. It is also important to note that many manufacturers use the 870 Express platform for their Police / Combat models. Without exception, every manufacturer who utilizes our 870 platform serves to upgrade their system to a more efficient, street worthy platform.

While the 870 Express is still an 870, the best pump shotgun on the market, there are some very important cosmetic and functional differences between it and the 870 Police. To our customers in Law Enforcement, Military, Corrections, and Security, whose lives depend upon the unfailing performance of Remington shotguns, the Police modifications are of paramount importance.Synopses of the variances are provided below.


870 Police shotguns go thru a special 23 station check list – ranging from visual inspection, functional testing, test firing, and final inspection.   
All Police shotguns are assembled in a “special build area” at the plant in Ilion, NY. This section is secured and serves only to build LE and Military shotguns, with the same factory personnel working at that assignment each shift.
All parts that enter the “special build area” are visually inspected by hand to ensure top quality and functionality.
Due to heavy recoil in buck and slug loads, all 870 Police guns have a longer magazine spring which ensures positive feed and function.   
A heavier sear spring is used to generate a reliable, positive trigger pull between 5 and 8 lbs.   
A heavier carrier dog spring is used to ensure when the carrier elevates the shell, it will be held there until the bolt can push it into the chamber. This ensures positive feeding when using heavier payload rounds.   
Police shotguns do not have an ISS (Integrated Safety System) which is a locking mechanism on the safety of commercial shotguns. This type of locking mechanism can cause delay to an officer who needs the weapon but does not have the appropriate key. LE shotguns have the standard, proven, cross bolt safety.   
The fore-end on the Express model is longer and not compatible with many police shotgun vehicle racks. The Police shotguns utilize the heavy duty SPEEDFEED Stocks and Fore-ends.   
The Express model will not allow for the addition of an extension tube without physical modification to the tube and barrel, which can nullify the warranty.   
The Express model has a BEAD BLAST BLUE finish while the Police models utilize Parkerization. The Express model utilizes a synthetic trigger housing while the Police models use a compressed metal housing.
The Police shotgun barrel is locked down with a “ball detent” system in conjunction with the magazine cap vs. a lesser grade “synthetic magazine spring retainer” lock down as used on the Express system.   
The receivers used in Police guns are “vibra honed” to smooth out rough finishes and remove burrs before parkerization.   
Police shotguns use machined ejectors and extractors, as opposed to powdered metal cast which are utilized on the Express models.
